name: FOSTER HOMES
description:
A tragic fire destroys the family home.  An unexpected job loss destines a family to move from a house to an apartment.  A health issue forces major life changes.  In each of these scenarios, and countless others, a beloved family dog loses the only home that it has known.

Washington German Shepherd Rescue can provide a safe and healing environment for these dogs by saving them from the stress and isolation of an animal shelter and an uncertain future.  But this is true only if there are enough foster families available to help.

Do you, or someone you know, have the time and extra space in your home and in your heart to foster one of these special dogs?  Have you considered adopting a dog, perhaps a second dog, but do not want to commit to a 12-15 year lifespan? Fostering a German Shepherd could be right for you!

German Shepherds long for companionship, enjoy exercise and are eager to learn. Foster homes can provide all of this and more by preparing the dog for his or her special new family. A soft bed to rest on; a gentle hand to provide comfort; a safe haven during an otherwise stressful period of their life. Fostering a displaced dog is both challenging and rewarding. Special people helping special dogs find their forever home.

Please email us directly at washingtonshepherds@yahoo.com for more information about this vital service of our rescue program.  Your help can make a tremendous difference in the lives of many dogs.

Rescue work is a great way to meet new people!  And our volunteers are invited to WGSR private events.

Are you following us on Facebook? Our Facebook account is updated daily with information about our rescue dogs and volunteer opportunities!

https://www.facebook.com/WashingtonGermanShepherdRescue

name: Nolan
description:
One of our volunteers came across this senior online.  This older GSD was located at one of the high kill shelters in California.  He was slated for euthanasia.  Why?  Because he is 9 years old.  These shelters are over flowing with dogs, and seniors never have a chance.

We were able to find someone to pull him from the shelter in time and take him right away to a veterinarian.

We are looking for a foster home for this senior GSD when he arrives into rescue next weekend!

If you have the space for a well deserving senior, please let us know!  We would love to gather some high quality food for this boy and some joint supplements for when he arrives!  If you are able to send a bag of food, please let us know!

name: Roxie
description:
Roxie is new to rescue!  This gorgeous, 18-month-old, female German Shepherd Dog has been well loved and cared for since she was a puppy.  Roxie was given lots of attention, training and an excellent food.  Her owner felt that he was no longer able to provide her with the continued training and attention she needed at her young age. 

Roxie's previous owner put an amazing training foundation in for her and she is all ready for her new home to continue with that!

Roxie is excellent on leash and off leash.  She loves to fetch and loves playing with the big neutral male shepherd-mix in her foster home.  Roxie has a  lot of energy, but also has an off switch when she's asked to calm down, such as when she goes to work with her foster mom or to the dog friendly restaurant in Seattle.  The foster home has also taken her on very short, slow jogs and she does great.

Roxie is living with a friendly cat who doesn't run away and Roxieâs great with her.  She's curious and friendly, but will back off when I tell her to.  She wouldnât be suited for a home with a cat that is skittish or runs.

Roxie has  met her foster mom's horse and has done really well, which is very impressive!  Curious, but not pushy.

Roxie is also a total cuddle bug and clearly spent her whole life snuggling on the couch or in bed, but will get down when told to without an issue.

Overall, anyone who adopts Roxie will be very lucky!  We prefer to adopt her locally within 1-2 hours of the Seattle area.

name: Merlin
description:
Merlin is new to rescue!  This adorable puppy is looking for a very specific home!

Merlin is looking for a home with high drive German Shepherd Dog experience or Malinois experience.  She needs to go to a home with very confident dogs.

Merlin has lots of energy, but she's highly trainable.  She needs a very active or sport dog home.  Merlin needs to have a job.

Lucy enjoys being admired by other people from afar when she is out on walks. 
 She also really enjoys playing with her foster brother.  (Video attached.)

This gorgeous girl is housebroken and is so well-mannered.  And we almost forget to mention that Lucy's foster mom is a highly regarded trainer in Seattle!  Lucy is so lucky she is in an amazing foster home mastering her obedience!

name: Kona
description:
Kona is a super sweet, affectionate, mostly mellow and very responsive dog!  He likes to cuddle, play ball and play with other dogs.  Kona has done great with dogs off leash so far, though gets distracted by them in training class and it's hard for him to pay attention to anything else. 

Kona's fur was a bit rough when we first got him, but we switched him to a grain-free food (Taste of the Wild) and put him on some salmon oil.  It looks great now!  He's a strikingly beautiful shepherd and gets lots of compliments. 

Kona's well-behaved in my home, though if I'm gone for more than an hour, I either take him in my car or leave him in his crate.  He does pretty well in cars, though dirt roads make him anxious and he then tries to crawl into the driver's seat and hide his head in my lap.  We're working on that...

We let him on one of our couches and Kona loves to lay next to us, but also listens if we tell him to get off and lie down while we are eating.  He doesn't know very many specific commands yet (and if stressed, doesn't follow the ones he knows) and we're working on good leash behavior, but I think he has lots of potential.

As Kona has spent more time here, he's gotten more protective of our home and sometimes barks a bit when someone knocks on the door.  He quiets down once we introduce him to someone or if we put him in his bed. 

Kona warms up quickly to women and kids, but is wary of some bigger guys at first.  That said, he has totally bonded to my partner, who is also a bigger guy. 

When we have multiple guests at once, we start with Kona in his crate so he can see that whomever we're introducing him to is a friend of ours, and then once everyone is settled and sitting (less intimidating for him), we let him out to say hi.  As long as it's not a big group and no one is too huge (we have one friend who is super big and Kona still doesn't like him around), he does great. We don't make him say hi to anyone he doesn't want to and instruct everyone to let him say hi to them, not vice versa - and to not reach out and pet him until he is clearly comfortable. 

We took him on some hikes and an overnight backpack--he did great in all the terrain we were on and was super fun to be around. We kept him on leash on the trail.  (Kona was good if leashed to the first person, but pulled forward if behind.)  We let him off leash when we left the trail.  Kona was fantastic off trail and off leash--stayed within sight and came back whenever called--we were super impressed. 

Kona has the potential for attachment anxiety in certain situations.  He has already bonded to both me and my partner and when my partner left our camp for a side trip that couldn't include Kona, Kona was very upset and spent the next couple hours yelping and trying pull away in the direction he had left.  After that situation, one of us would take him for a walk whenever the other was leaving so that he didn't see the departure take place, in which case no anxiety was triggered.  Kona does fine with us leaving at home, so I think this was in part a function of being in a new place and wanting his pack to stay together. 
 He's still adjusting to tent sleeping.  We couldn't believe he wasn't more exhausted after such a big day!

My sense is that Kona would do best in a living situation with another dog, as he has a lot of playful, but mouthy energy that could use a healthy and consistent outlet.  I also suspect he'd do best in a consistent environment that generally has the same people and not a lot of chaos.  Kona gets overwhelmed by big groups of people, big guys, and city landscapes.

Â She is working on potty training and crate trained but enjoys to be free and doesnât make a mess  and knows basic commands. Ruby has come a long way and is quickly learning to walk on a harness but could be very high energy when she sees other dogs. name: Artie
description: Hi, my name is Artie, and I am a five year old Lab/Golden mix boy searching for my forever home. I weigh about 65 pounds. I am house trained, walked well on leash, and I am used to being left loose alone in the house. I love attention and to hang out outside. I like to play with tennis balls and I do fetch! I take walks daily as well. I will do best as an only dog or with a medium to large size female dog. Please watch my Youtube video by clicking on the link right next to my pictures.

name: Angel
description: My name is Angel and I was found as a stray in Houston Tx over a year ago. The person who found me planned on taking me to a shelter, but when she realized I was deaf she decided to foster me and find me a forever home. Over year has passed and I am still waiting for that perfect family to love me and give me a chance. The lady who found m has gone above and beyond for me, but she now says she will humanely euthanize me if I don't find a forever home or foster by November 30th. I'm not sure what that means, but it sure does sound like something really bad. Brave Bully Rescue decided to share my story as they know I'm a great dog that deserves to be loved and taken care of. I am 3 years old, I love the outdoor life, so I can be lots of fun. I would do best with kids over the age of 8 since I get a little nervous with new situations. I do not do well with cats, but I do well with other dogs that are submissive. I was with a trainer for a couple of months and I did so great and met a lot of dogs so I know I am ready for my forever home. Please give me a chance before my life ends :-(

name: Logan
description:
Meet Logan!!

This sweet boy and his sister landed in a high kill shelter in 2017 for no fault of their own. His sister was lucky to get adopted at the shelter, but sadly poor Logan didn't get that lucky. Thanks to his loving foster we were able to save him and Logan was adopted in 2017, however he is now in need of a new home because his mom and dad can't give him the attention he needs due to having a newborn baby. Logan is a complete sweetheart with gorgeous honey colored eyes who loves to play with his toys and his little human foster brothers. He loves kids and is great with other well socialized, submissive dogs like himself. He is excellent in a crate, excellent on car rides, easy to walk on a leash and is housebroken. He is so soft you wonât want to stop petting him, and he doesnât mind.  He is good in crowds, and likes the attention of strangers petting him. He would love to be the dog you bring to the pet friendly brewery or a friends back yard barbeque. Your friends will rave about how well behaved your dog is. The only time you will ever hear him bark is when the pizza man rings the doorbell. Some of his favorite things include making babies laugh, licking your ears, tug of war, dinner time, and cuddling for nap time. Logan is  truly an amazing dog If you are looking for a wonderful family pet, look no more! Logan will bring lots of happiness into your home!


Note: Logan is located in Houston, however transport can be arrange. We have adopted over 15 dogs out of state and things have worked out great. Adoption fee does not include transport.

Adoption fee: $250. Does not include transport

name: Phoebe
description:
Meet Phoebe. This beautiful girl is only a year old and weights about 60 pounds. She was found as a stray in Houston Texas and like many others she was on the list to be euthanize. Phoebe was saved thanks to her amazing foster who decided to help this sweet girl. Phoebe knows basic commands, she walks good on a leash, she house broken, good on a crate, great with kids, and great with dogs. Phoebe is truly the perfect dog. She is super sweet and fun to be around. If you would like to meet this cutie and add her to your family please visit our website www.bravebullyrescue.org and fill out our adoption application.

*Phoebe is in Houston, but transportation can be arrange and foster can do a video call so you can meet our sweet girl.*

Adoption fee: $250. Does not include transport.

name: Tux
description:
Meet Tux,

This beautiful boy is about 6 months old. He was found by a Good Samaritan about a month ago. Tux had a collar and name tag, but when the owner was reached they lied and said they didn't know Tux. Is hard to understand how someone could have abandoned this baby. Tux is super sweet and fun. He is good on a crate, walks well on a leash and he is just lots of fun. To date he knows how to sit for his food, seeâs a leash and know itâs time for a walk. Consider adding Tux to your family, you will not regret giving this boy an opportunity. Tux is super sweet with humans, and well behaved, he has met a few dogs and has done great. He just needs proper introduction. 

Note: Tux is located in Houston, however transport can be arrange. We have adopted over 15 dogs out of state and things have worked out great. Adoption fee does not include transport.

Adoption fee: $250. Does not include transport

name: Falcor
description:
Falcor is an absolute love bug and wiggle-butt extraordinare. This gorgeous boy was adopted from our rescue when he was only 2 months old, but now that he is 4 years old his family had a baby and having a dog and a baby has become a lot for them so Falcor now needs to find a new home. He loves to give hugs and receive belly-rubs. He is very energetic, but also loves to cuddle with you on the couch or a pillow if you have one to spare for him. Falcor gets along very well with other equally minded dogs. He is an energetic type of dog so he will do best with a dog that also loves to play and is not super dominant. Falcor has lived with cats, but if the cat is aggressive towards him, he will react. He knows simple commands like sit, stay, lay down, shake and high-five with a treat as added incentive. He would do well with a small family with another canine buddy. He is good with kids and will stay by you on walks. We recommend he gave a yard to run about and explore. He does need daily attention and play to get out all his energy. With that you will have a loyal friend for life.

Note: Falcor is in Texas, but transportation can be arrange. The transport fee is $160.

name: Rolfie
description:

He is super playful and it gets along great with all dogs. He loves to have his head on you at all times, loves to snuggle and sleep under the covers. We are working on potty training. I believe he must have been trained to puppy pads he goes on those very well.
